Resolved... for now (?)

Normally what I do is require a CAPTCHA for edits that add a link. But since 
most of the point of our wiki is to accept links, that seems antisocial to me.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg270">msg270 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: pythonian4000</th>
   <th>Date: 2010-06-21.12:10:47</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre><a href="https://openhatch.org/wiki/Bug_trackers/requested">https://openhatch.org/wiki/Bug_trackers/requested</a> has somehow got itself onto a
botnet wiki spam list. The entire list of requested trackers gets replaced by
rather dodgy links. I have undone this twice now, so maybe it would be a good
idea to implement some form of defense against this?

Reading the MediaWiki page on combating spam
(<a href="http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Combating_spam">http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Combating_spam</a>) has several suggestions,
of which I think only two are worthwile - adding a CAPTCHA of some sort to the
editing page, or hooking the wiki up to a honey pot such as http:BL
(<a href="http://www.projecthoneypot.org/">http://www.projecthoneypot.org/</a>). Personally I prefer the second option, as it
impacts the users the least. (plus I googled one of the spammer IPs and the
first result was a listing on this blacklist - a good sign!)</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
